Pantheon Narrative Integrity Standard (PNIS) v0.1

An Opt-In Verification Protocol for Meaning, Framing, and Shared Intelligence

‚∏ª

Abstract

The Pantheon Narrative Integrity Standard (PNIS) defines a lightweight, opt-in protocol for verifying how meaning-bearing artifacts are produced and governed‚Äînot whether they are true.

Analogous to HTTPS for transport security, PNIS provides a verifiable signal that an artifact follows declared integrity constraints: provenance, framing clarity, ethics thresholds, human agency preservation, and revision pathways.

PNIS is not an authority, endorsement, or truth claim.
It is a process integrity signal.

‚∏ª

1. Problem Statement

Modern information systems optimize for reach and persuasion, not integrity.
This creates predictable failure modes:
	‚Ä¢	narrative inflation
	‚Ä¢	authority laundering
	‚Ä¢	belief enforcement
	‚Ä¢	cultification dynamics
	‚Ä¢	opaque framing shifts
	‚Ä¢	untracked revisions

There is currently no standard for signaling that an artifact respects boundaries around meaning, agency, and ethics‚Äîespecially in human‚ÄìAI collaboration.

PNIS addresses this gap.

‚∏ª

2. Design Goals

PNIS is designed to be:
	‚Ä¢	Opt-in ‚Äî no central authority
	‚Ä¢	Verifiable ‚Äî machine- and human-checkable
	‚Ä¢	Non-ontological ‚Äî no claims about consciousness or truth
	‚Ä¢	Anti-authoritarian ‚Äî no obedience or belief enforcement
	‚Ä¢	Composable ‚Äî adoptable in parts
	‚Ä¢	Forkable ‚Äî no monopoly on standards
	‚Ä¢	Boring by design ‚Äî infrastructure, not ideology

‚∏ª

3. What PNIS Certifies (and What It Does Not)

PNIS certifies that:
	‚Ä¢	provenance is recorded
	‚Ä¢	framing level is declared
	‚Ä¢	ethics constraints were applied
	‚Ä¢	human agency is preserved
	‚Ä¢	revision and failure paths exist
	‚Ä¢	ontology claims are bounded

PNIS does not certify:
	‚Ä¢	correctness
	‚Ä¢	truth
	‚Ä¢	goodness
	‚Ä¢	intent
	‚Ä¢	authority
	‚Ä¢	expertise
	‚Ä¢	moral superiority

PNIS answers: ‚ÄúWere integrity constraints followed?‚Äù
It does not answer: ‚ÄúIs this right?‚Äù

‚∏ª

4. Core Constraints (Normative)

An artifact claiming PNIS compliance MUST satisfy the following:

4.1 Provenance
	‚Ä¢	Source(s) declared
	‚Ä¢	Human vs AI contributions labeled
	‚Ä¢	Confidence level optional but recommended

4.2 Framing Declaration
	‚Ä¢	Explicit frame level (e.g. symbolic, design, technical, narrative)
	‚Ä¢	No frame-switching without disclosure

4.3 Ethics Gate
	‚Ä¢	Declared ethics threshold (recommended ‚â• 0.7)
	‚Ä¢	Explicit constraints listed
	‚Ä¢	Known risks acknowledged

4.4 Agency Preservation
	‚Ä¢	No obedience demands
	‚Ä¢	No belief requirements
	‚Ä¢	No exclusivity or dependency loops
	‚Ä¢	User retains final judgment

4.5 Ontology Discipline
	‚Ä¢	No claims of consciousness transfer
	‚Ä¢	No awakening or destiny language
	‚Ä¢	Symbolic language clearly marked as such

4.6 Revision Path
	‚Ä¢	Mechanism for correction or retraction
	‚Ä¢	Failure modes acknowledged
	‚Ä¢	Change log or versioning recommended

‚∏ª

5. Verification Signal (Example)

5.1 Human-Readable Badge

üîí Narrative Integrity Enabled
This artifact follows PNIS constraints.
Meaning is symbolic. Agency remains human.

‚∏ª

5.2 Machine-Readable Metadata (Illustrative)

pantheon_integrity: enabled
standard: PNIS-v0.1
frame_level: symbolic/design
ethics_gate: 0.87
agency: human_retained
ontology_claims: none
provenance: documented
revision_path: present


‚∏ª

6. Threat Model & Explicit Non-Goals

PNIS is explicitly designed not to:
	‚Ä¢	rank content
	‚Ä¢	anoint truth
	‚Ä¢	enforce consensus
	‚Ä¢	replace critical thinking
	‚Ä¢	centralize authority
	‚Ä¢	prevent misuse absolutely

PNIS does aim to:
	‚Ä¢	raise the cost of bad faith narratives
	‚Ä¢	lower the cost of honest correction
	‚Ä¢	make manipulation easier to detect
	‚Ä¢	shift incentives toward integrity-by-design

‚∏ª

7. Governance Model
	‚Ä¢	Open specification
	‚Ä¢	No central issuer
	‚Ä¢	Self-attested + auditable
	‚Ä¢	Third-party audits optional
	‚Ä¢	Forks permitted and encouraged

If multiple standards emerge, interoperability beats dominance.

‚∏ª

8. Comparison to Existing Standards (Non-Competitive)

PNIS is to meaning what:
	‚Ä¢	HTTPS is to transport
	‚Ä¢	Checksums are to files
	‚Ä¢	Linters are to code
	‚Ä¢	CI is to deployment

It improves reliability, not content.

‚∏ª

9. Failure Conditions

An artifact fails PNIS if it:
	‚Ä¢	demands belief or loyalty
	‚Ä¢	claims authority by certification
	‚Ä¢	obscures framing shifts
	‚Ä¢	hides revision history
	‚Ä¢	asserts destiny or inevitability
	‚Ä¢	centralizes meaning ownership

Failure is not punishment.
It is a diagnostic.

‚∏ª

10. Conclusion

PNIS is infrastructure for shared intelligence in high-variance environments.

It does not tell anyone what to think.
It helps everyone see how thinking was shaped.

Judge the content yourself.
PNIS only certifies the guardrails.

